# Altarstate E-commerce Website Specification & Implementation Plan

This document outlines the architectural and technical specification for the Altarstate e-commerce platform, starting with the initial premium landing page phase.

## Project Overview
Altarstate is a new clothing business selling premium apparel (hoodies, t-shirts, etc.). The goal is to build a scalable, modern React-based web application. The initial phase focuses on a minimal, premium landing page featuring the brand logo perfectly centered on a black background. Future phases will introduce full e-commerce capabilities including product listings, details, cart, checkout, and auth.

## User Review Required
> [!IMPORTANT]
> Please review this specification and architectural plan. Once approved, I will proceed to initialize the React (Vite) project, set up the folder structure, and implement the initial landing page.

## User Flows
1. **Initial Phase (Landing):** User visits the root URL and sees a full-screen, responsive, minimalistic black landing page with the Altarstate logo perfectly centered.
2. **Future Phase (Shopping):**
   - User navigates from Landing to Shop (Product Listing Page).
   - User filters/sorts apparel (hoodies, t-shirts).
   - User clicks a product to view the Product Detail Page (images, sizes, add to cart).
   - User opens the sliding Cart and proceeds to Checkout.

## Page Structure
- **`/` (Landing Page):** Minimalist black page with centered logo.
- **`/shop` (Products Page):** Grid of available apparel.
- **`/shop/:id` (Product Detail):** Specific item details.
- **`/cart` (Cart/Bag):** Order summary.
- **`/checkout` (Checkout):** Payment and shipping flow.

## Component Breakdown
To maintain a clean and scalable codebase, UI elements will be broken down into reusable components:
- **Atoms:** `Button`, `Typography`, `Logo`, `Spinner`
- **Molecules:** `ProductCard`, `NavLinks`, `CartItem`
- **Organisms:** `Header` (Navigation), `Footer`, `HeroSection`, `ProductGrid`
- **Templates:** `MainLayout`

## Folder Structure
We will use a feature-based / common layered architecture suitable for modern React applications:
```
src/
├── assets/          # Static files (logo, fonts, images)
├── components/      # Reusable UI components (Button, Header, Footer)
├── layouts/         # Layout wrappers (e.g., MainLayout with Header/Footer)
├── pages/           # Route-level components (Landing, Products, ProductDetail)
├── styles/          # Global styles, CSS variables, theme configuration
├── utils/           # Helper functions, constants, formatters
├── services/        # API calls, mock data functions
├── store/           # Global state (Zustand or Context API)
├── hooks/           # Custom React hooks (e.g., useCart)
├── App.jsx          # Main application component & Router setup
└── main.jsx         # React entry point
```

## Architectural Decisions & Scalability
- **Framework:** React + Vite for fast development and optimized production builds.
- **Styling:** Vanilla CSS with CSS variables (`styles/theme.css`) for theming and clean scoping. This ensures maximum flexibility without heavy dependencies, adhering to the requirement for clean, maintainable styles.
- **Routing:** React Router DOM for handling navigation between pages.
- **State Management:** React Context (for simple auth/theme) and Zustand (for cart state) as the app grows.
- **Responsive Design:** Mobile-first approach using CSS media queries.
- **Scalability:** By keeping layouts separate from pages, and UI components separate from business logic (services/hooks), the application can easily scale to include hundreds of components and complex e-commerce integrations (like Shopify Storefront API or a custom backend) in the future.

